data.content:
Yes! MSTest v3.8+ introduced the generic `DynamicData<T>` attribute, which gives you compile-time type safety using tuples:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
[DynamicData<(string, bool)>(nameof(TestData))]
public void Validate_ReturnsExpected(string input, bool expected)
{
    var result = Validator.IsValid(input);
    Assert.AreEqual(expected, result);
}

public static IEnumerable<(string input, bool expected)> TestData =>
[
    ("valid@email.com", true),
    ("invalid", false),
    ("", false),
];
```

**What changed:**
- `DynamicData` → `DynamicData<(string, bool)>` — tuple type params are checked at compile time
- `IEnumerable<object[]>` → `IEnumerable<(string, bool)>` — no more boxing or type mismatches at runtime
- Array syntax `["x", true]` → tuple syntax `("x", true)`

If any test data row has the wrong types, you'll get a compiler error instead of a runtime failure. Requires the `MSTest.TestFramework` 3.8+ NuGet package.
